foliation.note: Numbering in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the rectos.
f. 174 has been pasted on the rear cover.

list.item: Quire 1510-4 (ff. 169-180: 6th leaf, f. 174, is the pastedown on the rear cover, 7th-10th cancelled

signatures.p: Arabic numerals in crayon (?) written in the lower margins of the first halves of quires.

catchwords.seg: Catchwords in frames of brown ink in the lower right-hand corners of the last versos of quires.

layout.seg: Ruled in crayon, frame and line ruling. Double columns. 44 lines to the page, written below top line.

handNote.p: Copied by a single scribe in a Northern Textualis script [Gothic Rotunda according to Thomson].

decoNote.p: Large (4-8 lines) puzzle initial in blue and red with red penwork decoration inside the letter featuring floral motifs and pen-flourishing in red (ff. 1r, 25r, 41r, 56r, 76v, 98r, 113v, 144r); except for one (f. 1r) which features a hybrid figure and a partial (1-sided) J-border in blue and red (ff. 1r)
Small (2 lines) initials in blue or red with penwork decoration and pen-flourishing in the opposite colour (but red initials also are flourised in blue-green)
Titles and subheadings in red ink.
Paraphs in blue or red ink.
Drawings of human faces in brown ink extending from the text space in to the margins (f. 3r)

note.p: Below the catchword on f. 96v is a pencilled calculation by a scribe or rubricator.

Table of contents added by a 17th-century hand (perhaps the same hand that inscribed the title inscriptions on the spine) in the upper margin of f. 1r: Constantin[us] l[iber] v[iaticum] [...] 1536 cu[m] co[mmentarium] Girardi / Glosulae 4or Magistrorum in Chirurgiam.
Quire numbers in the right-hand corners of the first rectos written in pencil by a 20th-century hand.

binding.p: Vellum binding over pasteboards: the vellum consists of a reused lease from Peterhouse, dated to 1750 [? according to Thomson], with the reverse turned outward; three horizontal slits on vellum on the front cover may have been used for a seal. An unidentified early modern printed text has been pasted underneath the vellum. The spine is inscribed with a title inscription in brown ink: 'Constantinus - de curatione morborum', a former (?) classmark '1-1 1', and an unread transcription with the date '1700'; it also features a paper lable with the printed number '106'.

history.acquisition: Recorded in the catalogue of Peterhouse books on 24 December 1418 (see CBMLC10, UC48.294) and no. 218 in Thomas James' Ecloga Oxonio-Catabrigiensis (1600). Peterhouse's book stamp in the lower margins of ff. 1r and 93r.

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws substantially on R. M. Thomson, A Descriptive Catalogue of the Medieval Manuscripts in the Library of Peterhouse, Cambridge (Woodbridge, 2016). Readers of this record are strongly encouraged to consult Thomson's Catalogue for further information. This catalogue entry also draws on M. R. James, A descriptive catalogue of the manuscripts in the library of Peterhouse (Cambridge: Cambridge University Library 1899).

availability.p: The majority of the western medieval manuscripts owned by Peterhouse, including MS 106, are on long-term deposit at Cambridge University Library. Entry to read in Cambridge University Library is permitted only on presentation of a valid reader's card. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library). For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.
